---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { pdfLinks } from '../data/publicationLinks';

const p = pdfLinks;
---

<BaseLayout title="Research Themes" description="Paul Platzer — Research Themes">
  <h1>Research Themes</h1>

  <h2>Weather and Ocean Analogs</h2>

  <p>
    My main research theme is weather/ocean analogs. It is a striking
    property of the atmospheric and ocean circulation that most observed patterns
    are recurring, i.e. similar patterns have been previously observed in the
    past and will be in the future. Here is an analog versus non-analog
    comparison for (linearly detrended) 500mb geopotential-height (z500) over the Northern Hemisphere
    (data = ERA5 reanalysis, 1979-2023, winter DJF, daily 12utc, preprocessing = pointwise linear detrending).
  </p>

  <figure class="research-figure">
    <img
      src="/assets/figures/z500_analog_vs_nonanalog_detrended_values.png"
      alt="Comparison of analog and non-analog 500hPa geopotential height patterns over the Northern Hemisphere"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption>
      Analog and non-analog z500 patterns over the Northern Hemisphere (ERA5 reanalysis).
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The large-scale atmospheric circulation on this part of the earth is largely
    driven by the jet-stream, which is a main driver of mid-latitude weather
    conditions. The jet stream always flows from West to East, along
    constant geopotential-height contours. The particular configuration of the
    jet stream (shape and intensity) varies non-linearly (chaotically) and
    the latter typically forms meanders, caused by a meteorological phenomenon called
    &lsquo;Rossby waves&rsquo;. Most of the configurations of the
    jet-stream are recurring and will &lsquo;come back&rsquo; every
    few years. Here, the circulation on 1994-12-26 was analogous to that of
    2006-12-12, with the jet stream extending in a direction from the North Pacific
    to the North-East Atlantic (troughs), and contracting along the opposite direction (ridges).
    Contrarily, on 2008-12-15, the jet stream extended towards North-America and North-East Russia,
    with geopotential height forming a bipolar pattern. The normalized Euclidean distance between
    these fields is shown, where a distance equal to 1 corresponds to the typical distance between
    two randomly selected z500 fields.
  </p>

  <p>
    Here is another analog versus non-analog example using sea-surface
    temperature data (data = ERSSTv5, 1854-2026,  monthly, summer JJA, preprocessing = pointwise linear detrending).
  </p>

  <figure class="research-figure">
    <img
      src="/assets/figures/sst_analog_vs_nonanalog_anomaly.png"
      alt="Comparison of analog and non-analog sea-surface temperature anomaly patterns"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <figcaption>
      Analog and non-analog SST anomaly patterns (ERSSTv5).
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>I am interested in understanding the properties of analog-based statistical methods, covering several aspects:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      the properties of analog forecasts
      {p['Platzer2021a_JAS'] && <span class="pubref"> (<a href={p['Platzer2021a_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2024_STUOD'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2024_STUOD']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2024, STUOD proceedings</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the estimation of dimensions using analogs
      {p['Platzer2023_STUOD'] && <span class="pubref"> (<a href={p['Platzer2023_STUOD']}>Platzer et al. 2023, STUOD Proceedings</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2025'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2025']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2025, JSP</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2025_npj'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2025_npj']}>Platzer et al. 2025, npj clim. and atm. sc.</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the estimation of uncertainties using analogs, especially predictability, and extreme events
      {p['Platzer2021a_JAS'] && <span class="pubref"> (<a href={p['Platzer2021a_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021a, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2021b_JAS'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2021b_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021b, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2024_STUOD'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2024_STUOD']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2024, STUOD proceedings</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2024_CP'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2024_CP']}>Platzer et al. 2024, CP</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the optimization of analog methods, in particular the definition of analog distance, using
      gradient-descent-based algorithms
      {p['Platzer2025_MWR'] && <span class="pubref"> (<a href={p['Platzer2025_MWR']}>Platzer et al. 2025, MWR</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the application of analog methods in relationship to AI algorithms such as AI weather
      forecasting (in preparation).
    </li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
